Artificial Intelligence

AI algorithms implement rules derived from theory or first principles

  • Chess playing computers
  • Auto-pilot airplanes
  • Heat guided missiles

In contrast, Machine Learning uses data to train algorithms

Machine Learning Examples

  • Hand writing detection implemented by the postal service
  • Speech recognition (Siri)
  • Movie and other recommendation systems
  • Predicting hospitalization days from claims
  • Spam detectors

General Set-up

We want to be able to predict an outcome based on features:

outcome feature_1 feature_2 feature_3 feature_4 feature_5
? X_1 X_2 X_3 X_4 X_5

We want a function \( \,f \) that takes the \( X\mbox{s} \) and predicts an outcome.

The 784 features

Notation

For observation \( i \) we define the vector of \( p \) features

\[ \mathbf{X}_i = (X_{i,1},\dots,X_{i,p}) \]

For the digits example \( \,j=1,\dots,p \mbox{ with } p=784 \)

\( X_{i,j} \) is the intensity of j-th feature

Conditional Probabilities

  • For categorical problems \( Y \) can be one of \( K \) classes.

  • \( Y \) can be \( 1, 2, \dots, \) or \( K \)

  • To make a rational prediction we need

\[ f_k(x) \equiv \mbox{Pr}(Y=k \mid \mathbf{X}=\mathbf{x}), k=1,\dots,K \]

  • \( f_k(x) \) is called a prediction rule

  • Machine Learning is all about estimating \( \,f_k(x) \)

Binary Data

  • Many examples are binary. Example: fraud detection

  • In this case we use \( k=0,1 \)

For binary data

\[ \mbox{Pr}(Y=1 \mid \mathbf{X}=\mathbf{x}) \]

is the proportion of 1s in the \( \mathbf{X}=\mathbf{x} \) stratum

Conditional Expectations

Many of the algorithms can be applied to both categorical and continuous because if \( Y \) is binary:

\[ f(x) \equiv \mbox{E}(Y \mid \mathbf{X}=\mathbf{x})=\mbox{Pr}(Y=1 \mid \mathbf{X}=\mathbf{x}) \].

For continuous problems we estimate \( \mbox{E}(Y \mid \mathbf{X}=\mathbf{x}) \) because it minimizes

\[ \mbox{E}\{ (\hat{Y} - Y)^2 \mid \mathbf{X}=\mathbf{x} \} \]

Loss Function

We are tasked with developing a Machine Learning algorithm that given the height of the father \( X \) predicts the height of the son \( Y \).

How will we be judged?

We need to choose a loss function

A typical one is:

\[ (Y - \hat{Y})^2 \]

Loss Function

Because we consider \( Y \) is a random variable:

\[ \mbox{E}\left\{ (Y - \hat{Y})^2 \right\} \]

We can show mathematically, that the \( \hat{Y} \) that minimizes this quantity for an \( X=x \) is the conditional expectation

\[ \mbox{E}\left( Y \mid X=x\right) \]

Regression

Based on this plot we try:

\[ f(x) = \mbox{Pr}( Y = 1 | X=x) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x \]

Estimate \( \beta_0 \) and \( \beta_1 \) with least squares.

Our prediction rule will be: \[ \hat{f}(x) = \hat{\beta}_0+ \hat{\beta}_1 x \]

Logistic Regression

We wrote down :

\[ f(x) = \mbox{Pr}( y = 1 | X=x) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x \]

But expression on the right can be any real number while left is between 0 and 1.

General idea is to transform \( \mbox{Pr}( y = 1 | X=x) \):

\[ g(p) = \log \left( \frac{p}{1-p} \right) \]

Logit Transformation

Assessment

Remake the plot from the previous assessment but this time plot \( \,g(\hat{f}) \).

To avoid infinities, convert 1 to 0.99 and 0 to 0.01 and remove \( X>70 \)

Logistic regression

Fits the following model:

\[ g\left\{ \mbox{E}(Y \mid X=x) \right\} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x \]

Instead of least squares we compute the maximum likelihood estimate (MLE).

For about MLE in Statistical Theory course.

Logistic Regression

fit <- dat %>% filter(train) %>% 
  glm(truth ~ height, data=., 
      family = "binomial")

dat <- dat %>% 
  mutate(glm_f_hat = 
           predict(fit, newdata = dat, 
                   type="response")) %>%
  mutate(glm_pred=round(f_hat))

You can get help with ?glm and ?predict.glm

Bayes' Rule

In Machine Learning we refer to the prediction rule we would use if we knew

\[ \mbox{Pr}(Y=1 \mid \mathbf{X}=\mathbf{x}) \]

as Bayes' rule

This will be the best we can do.

But in practice we don't know this function.

Instead, we estimate it.

Naive Bayes

Estimate conditional probabilities using Bayes' theorem.

With binary outcome and one continuous predictor we have:

\[ d(x) = \mbox{Pr}(Y=1|X=x) \] with \[ \mbox{Pr}(Y=1|X=x) = \frac{\pi p_{X|Y=1}(x)} {(1-\pi) p_{X|Y=0}(x) + \pi p_{X|Y=1}(x)} \]

\( p \) represents probability density function.

\( \pi \) is probability of \( Y=1 \)

Naive Bayes

In this problem we can use the normal approximation in which case we estimate averages and standard deviations

We can estimate \( \pi \) like this

pi <- filter(dat, train) %>% summarize(pi=mean(truth)) %>% .$pi

And the parameters of distribution function like this:

params <- dat %>% filter(train) %>% group_by(gender) %>% summarize(avg = mean(height), sd = sd(height))

Parameter Estimates

pi

[1] 0.56

params

Source: local data frame [2 x 3]

  gender   avg    sd
   (chr) (dbl) (dbl)
1 Female    65   2.8
2   Male    70   3.1

Naive Bayes

The prediction rule is then:

x <- dat$height
p0 <- dnorm(x, params$avg[1], params$sd[1])
p1 <- dnorm(x, params$avg[2], params$sd[2])
f_hat <- pi*p1/(pi*p1 + (1-pi)*p0)

Naive Bayes

In this case it is very similar to regression approaches
